\[R_{K,\bm{w}}^{f}(\bm{u})=f(\bm{u})-\sum_{i=0}^{K}\sum_{|\bm{\alpha}|=i}\frac{D ^{\bm{\alpha}}f(\bm{w})}{\bm{\alpha}!}\cdot(\bm{u}-\bm{w})^{\bm{\alpha}}.\] (3)

Given matrices \(\mathbf{Q}\) and \(\mathbf{P}\) in \(\mathbb{R}^{\ell_{1}\times\ell_{2}}\) we claim that \(\mathbf{Q}\leq\mathbf{P}\) if \([\mathbf{Q}]_{i,j}-[\mathbf{P}]_{i,j}\leq 0\) for every \(i,j\). For a sequence of vector-valued functions \(\{\bm{F}_{i}\}_{i=1}^{d}\), we say that \(\{\bm{F}_{i}\}_{i=1}^{d}\) is uniformly \(L\)-Lipschitz continuous with respect to \(\|\cdot\|\) under \(\|\cdot\|\) if \(\left\|\bm{F}_{i}\left(\bm{x}_{i}\right)-\bm{F}_{i}\left(\bm{u}_{i}\right) \right\|\), \(\leq L\|\bm{x}_{i}-\bm{u}_{i}\|\) for every \(i\in[1:d]\) and any \(\bm{x},\bm{u}\in\mathcal{X}\). We denote by \(\|\cdot\|\), the dual norm of \(\|\cdot\|\). Let \(\mathbf{P}:\mathbb{R}^{\ell_{1}\times\ell_{2}}\to\mathbb{R}^{n_{1}\times n_{2}}\) be a matrix function, we say that \(\mathbf{P}\) is a \(\theta\)-contraction mapping under \(\|\cdot\|\) if \(\left\|\mathbf{P}(\mathbf{Q}_{1})-\mathbf{P}(\mathbf{Q}_{2})\right\|_{\infty} \leq\theta\|\mathbf{Q}_{1}-\mathbf{Q}_{2}\|\) for any \(\mathbf{Q}_{1},\mathbf{Q}_{2}\in\mathbb{R}^{\ell_{1}\times\ell_{2}}\). For matrix-valued function \(\mathbf{P}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{\ell_{1}\times\ell_{2}}\),we define \(\mathbf{D}_{\mathbf{P}}(\bm{x},\bm{x}^{\prime})=\mathbf{P}(\bm{x})-\mathbf{P}( \bm{x}^{\prime})\) for any \(\bm{x},\bm{x}^{\prime}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}\). The KL divergence \(\mathrm{KL}(\bm{p}\|\bm{q})=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\bm{p}(\bm{p})\cdot\log\left(\frac{ \bm{p}(j)}{\bm{q}(j)}\right)\) between distributions \(\bm{p}\) and \(\bm{q}\) is defined on probability simplex \(\Delta_{n}\). And the variance of \(\bm{x}\) over \(\bm{p}\) is defined by \(\mathrm{Var}_{\bm{p}}(\bm{x})=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\bm{p}(j)\cdot\left(\bm{x}(j)- \mathbb{E}_{j^{\prime}\sim\bm{p}}[\bm{x}(j^{\prime})]\right)^{2}\). We define max-min gap of function \(f:\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{Y}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}\) as follows,

\[\mathcal{G}_{f}(\bm{x},\bm{y}):=\max_{\bm{y}^{\prime}\in\mathcal{Y}}f(\bm{x}, \bm{y}^{\prime})-\min_{\bm{x}^{\prime}\in\mathcal{X}}f(\bm{x}^{\prime},\bm{y}).\] (4)

We claim that \((\bm{x},\bm{y})\) is an \(\varepsilon\)-approximate Nash equilibrium (\(\varepsilon\)-approximate NE) if \(\mathcal{G}_{f}(\bm{x},\bm{y})\leq\varepsilon\). When \(\varepsilon=0\), \((\bm{x},\bm{y})\) is a Nash equilibrium.

**Infinite Horizon Discounted Markov Decision Process:** We consider the setting of an infinite horizon discounted Markov decision process (MDP), denoted by \(\mathcal{M}:=(\mathcal{S},\mathcal{A},\mathbb{F},\sigma,\theta,\bm{\rho}_{0})\). \(\mathcal{S}\) is a finite state space; \(\mathcal{A}\) is a finite action space; \(\mathbb{P}(s|s^{\prime},a^{\prime})\) denotes the probability of transitioning from \(s\) to \(s^{\prime}\) under playing action \(a^{\prime}\); \(\sigma:\mathcal{S}\times\mathcal{A}\rightarrow[0,1]\) is a cost function, which quantifies the cost associated with taking action \(a\) in state \(s\); \(\theta\in[0,1)\) is a discount factor; \(\bm{\rho}_{0}\) is an initial state distribution over \(\mathcal{S}\).

\(\bm{\pi}:\mathcal{S}\rightarrow\Delta_{\mathcal{A}}\) (where \(\Delta_{\mathcal{A}}\) is the probability simplex over \(\mathcal{A}\)) denotes a stochastic policy, i.e., the agent play actions according to \(a\sim\bm{\pi}(\cdot|s)\). We use \(\mathbf{Pr}_{t}^{\bm{\pi}}(s^{\prime}|s)=\mathbf{Pr}^{\bm{\pi}}(s_{t}=s^{ \prime}|s_{0}=s)\) to denote the probability of visiting the state \(s^{\prime}\) from the state \(s\) after \(t\) time steps according to policy \(\bm{\pi}\). Let trajectory \(\tau=\{(s_{t},a_{t})\}_{t=0}^{\infty}\), where \(s_{0}\sim\bm{\rho}_{0}\), and, for all subsequent time steps \(t\), \(a_{t}\sim\bm{\pi}(\cdot|s_{t})\) and \(s_{t+1}\sim\mathbb{P}(\cdot|s_{t},a_{t})\). The value function \(V^{\bm{\pi}}:\mathcal{S}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}\) is defined as the discounted sum of future cost starting at state \(s\) and executing \(\bm{\pi}\), i.e.

\[V^{\bm{\pi}}(s)=(1-\theta)\mathbb{E}\left[\left.\sum_{t=0}^{\infty}\theta^{t} \sigma(s_{t},a_{t})\right|\bm{\pi},s_{0}=s\right].\]

Moreover, we define the action-value function \(Q^{\bm{\pi}}:\mathcal{S}\times\mathcal{A}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}\) and the advantage function \(A^{\bm{\pi}}:\mathcal{S}\times\mathcal{A}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}\) as follows:

\[Q^{\bm{\pi}}(s,a)=(1-\theta)\mathbb{E}\left[\left.\sum_{t=0}^{\infty}\theta^{ t}\sigma(s_{t},a_{t})\right|\bm{\pi},s_{0}=s,a_{0}=a\right],\;\;A^{\bm{\pi}}(s,a)=Q^{ \bm{\pi}}(s,a)-V^{\bm{\pi}}(s).\]

It's also useful to define the discounted state visitation distribution \(\bm{d}_{s_{0}}^{\bm{\pi}}\) of a policy \(\bm{\pi}\) as \(\bm{d}_{s_{0}}^{\bm{\pi}}(s)=(1-\theta)\sum_{t=0}^{\infty}\theta^{t}\mathbf{ Pr}_{t}^{\bm{\pi}}(s|s_{0})\). In order to simplify notation, we write \(\bm{d}_{\bm{\rho}_{0}}^{\bm{\pi}}(s)=\mathbb{E}_{s_{0}\sim\bm{\rho}_{0}}[\bm{d} _{s_{0}}^{\bm{\pi}}(s)]\), where \(\bm{d}_{\bm{\rho}_{0}}^{\bm{\pi}}\) is the discounted state visitation distribution under initial distribution \(\bm{\rho}_{0}\).

## 3 Minimization Optimization

In this section, we propose the generalized quasar-convexity (GQC) condition, and analyze a related algorithmic framework for minimization over \(\mathcal{X}=\prod_{i=1}^{d}\Delta_{n_{i}}\), under mild assumptions.

### Generalized Quasar-Convexity (GQC)

We provide a novel depiction of function structure-generalized quasar-convexity, which is defined as follows:

**Definition 3.1** (Generalized Quasar-Convexity (GQC)).: Let \(\bm{x}^{*}\in\mathcal{X}\subset\mathbb{R}^{\sum_{i=1}^{d}n_{i}}\) be a minimizer of the function \(f:\mathcal{X}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}\). We say that \(f\) is generalized quasar-convex on \(\mathcal{X}\) with respect to \(\bm{x}^{*}\) if for all \(\bm{x}\in\mathcal{X}\), there exist a sequence of vector-valued functions \(\{\bm{F}_{i}:\mathcal{X}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{n_{i}}\}_{i=1}^{d}\) and a sequence of positive scalars \(\{\gamma_{i}\}_{i=1}^{d}\) such that

\[f(\bm{x}^{*})\geq f(\bm{x})+\sum_{i=1}^{d}\frac{1}{\gamma_{i}}\left\langle\bm{F} _{i}(\bm{x}),\bm{x}_{i}^{*}-\bm{x}_{i}\right\rangle.\] (5)

If Eq. (5) holds, we say that \(\bm{F}=(\bm{F}_{1}^{\top},\cdots,\bm{F}_{d}^{\top})^{\top}\) is the internal function of \(f\). Given \(i\in[1:d]\) we say that \(\bm{F}_{i}\) is the internal function of \(f\) for variable block \(\bm{x}_{i}\).

Our proposed GQC condition concerns the multi-variable generalized extension of the quasar-convexity condition. In the case \(d=1\), the GQC condition degenerates into the \(\gamma\)-quasar-convexity condition as studied in Hinder et al. [24] with the gradient \(\nabla f(\bm{x})\) belongs to the internal functions of \(f\). In the case \(d>1\), the GQC condition is instrumental in capturing the crucial characteristic of those optimization applications with each variable block has difficulty to be optimized.

### Main Results

Recall that GQC condition provides a perspective to bound function error \(f(\bm{x})-f(\bm{x}^{*})\) based on internal function, which is different from that based on gradient oracle. We therefore aim to provide an algorithmic framework for finding an approximate suboptimal global solution using internal function. Given an objective function \(f:\mathcal{X}\to\mathbb{R}\) with internal function \(\bm{F}\), our algorithm (Algorithm 1) independently computes points \(\bm{g}_{i}^{t}\) and \(\bm{x}_{i}^{t}\) following OMD over each block. If \(\max_{i\in[1:d]}\gamma_{i}<\infty\) and internal function \(\bm{F}\) has Lipschitz continuity, we have following basic and primary convergence result of Algorithm 1,

**Theorem 3.2**.: _Assuming that \(\bm{F}\) is \(L\)-Lipschitz continuous with respect to \(\|\cdot\|_{*}\) under \(\|\cdot\|\) and \(\gamma_{\max}=\max_{i\in[1:d]}\gamma_{i}<\infty\), and setting \(\eta=(L^{2}d\gamma_{\max}\sum_{i=1}^{d}\gamma_{i}^{-1})^{-1/2}/2\), we have_

\[\frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^{T}(f(\bm{x}^{t})-f(\bm{x}^{*}))\leq\frac{2L\max_{i\in[1 :d]}\log(n_{i})\left(d\gamma_{\max}\right)^{1/2}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{d}\gamma_{i} ^{-1}\right)^{3/2}}{T}.\] (6)

However, the estimation provided by Theorem 3.2 depends on \(d\gamma_{\max}\). And the step size relying on \(\gamma_{\max}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{d}\gamma_{i}^{-1}\right)\) might be difficult to set when \(\{\gamma_{i}\}_{i=1}^{d}\) is unknown.

We then hope to propose an alternative analytical method that can adapt to unknown \(\{\gamma_{i}\}_{i=1}^{d}\) and obtain complexity which does not depends on block dimension \(d\) explicitly. The challenges includes: 1) The algorithm does not know the weight \(1/\gamma_{i}\); 2) every \(\bm{F}_{i}\) has dependence on the joint variable \(\bm{x}\) instead of depending on \(\bm{x}_{i}\). Before we present the details of convergence analysis, we need the following notations and assumptions:

Denote \(P_{K,\bm{y}}^{\ell}(\bm{x}))=\sum_{i=0}^{K}\sum_{|\bm{\alpha}|=i}\frac{|D^{ \bm{\alpha}}f(\bm{y})|}{\bm{\alpha}!}\cdot(|\bm{x}|+|\bm{y}|)^{\bm{\alpha}}\) and let \(\bm{P}_{K,\bm{y}}^{\bm{\phi}}(\bm{x})=(P_{K,\bm{y}}^{\bm{\phi}(1)}(\bm{x}), \cdots,\)\(P_{K,\bm{y}}^{\bm{\phi}(\ell)}(\bm{x}))\) for any vector-valued function \(\bm{\phi}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{\ell}\). Recalling the definition of \(R_{K,\bm{w}}^{\ell}\) in Eq. (3), we shall also define \(\bm{R}_{K,\bm{y}}^{\bm{\phi}}(\bm{x})=(R_{K,\bm{y}}^{\bm{\phi}(1)}(\bm{x}), \cdots,R_{K,\bm{y}}^{\bm{\phi}(\ell)}(\bm{x}))\).

